From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: James M <f0rm4tm3@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 28 Jun 2026 15:00:00 -0700
Subject: [PATCH v3 2/2] kernelbase: Don't dereference NULL start in
 CharPrevA/CharPrevExA.

When start is NULL, both functions dereference it in the loop condition.
Native Windows (measured via MSVC probe on GitHub Actions windows-latest)
returns the previous character pointer without crashing:

  CharPrevA(NULL, str + 1) returns str
  CharPrevA(NULL, str + 2) returns str + 1

For the tested ASCII/CP_ACP cases this is equivalent to ptr - 1.
DBCS backtracking (e.g. CP932) is left for a follow-up; the current
fix matches Windows for single-byte code pages only.
---
 dlls/kernelbase/string.c | 2 ++
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)

diff --git a/dlls/kernelbase/string.c b/dlls/kernelbase/string.c
index f83ae35..7b28227 100644
--- a/dlls/kernelbase/string.c
+++ b/dlls/kernelbase/string.c
@@ -1127,6 +1127,7 @@ LPWSTR WINAPI CharNextW(const WCHAR *x)
 
 LPSTR WINAPI CharPrevA(const char *start, const char *ptr)
 {
+    if (!start) return (LPSTR)(ptr - 1);
     while (*start && (start < ptr))
     {
         LPCSTR next = CharNextA(start);
@@ -1138,6 +1139,7 @@ LPSTR WINAPI CharPrevA(const char *start, const char *ptr)
 
 LPSTR WINAPI CharPrevExA(WORD codepage, const char *start, const char *ptr, DWORD flags)
 {
+    if (!start) return (LPSTR)(ptr - 1);
     while (*start && (start < ptr))
     {
         LPCSTR next = CharNextExA(codepage, start, flags);
